@page "/about"
@layout PublicLayout

<PageTitle>About — Nornis</PageTitle>

<article class="nornis-public-page">
    <div class="nornis-eyebrow">About</div>
    <h1>What Nornis is</h1>

    <p>
        Nornis is a world memory engine for tabletop roleplaying games. It helps players and
        GMs capture what happened, transform those raw sources into structured world
        knowledge, and consult that knowledge through an AI Loremaster.
    </p>
    <p>
        Nornis is not a wiki. It is not a folder tree, a notebook, or a document archive. Those
        exist as supporting views, but the product is the transformation itself: session notes,
        journals, transcripts, and handouts become artifacts, relationships, storylines, and
        canon — each carrying its provenance back to the source that produced it.
    </p>

    <h2>What we believe</h2>
    <p>
        <strong>Sources are raw material; artifacts are memory.</strong> A world grows from
        many inputs — notes, rumors, choices, consequences. Nornis gathers them and shapes them
        into an enduring record.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>AI proposes. Your table decides.</strong> Nothing enters accepted canon without a
        person saying yes. Every AI-proposed change is reviewable, editable, and rejectable, and
        every accepted fact can be traced to the source that supports it.
    </p>
    <p>
        <strong>Truth has texture.</strong> A world's reality includes confirmed facts,
        rumors, disputed accounts, known misinformation, and secrets the players haven't earned
        yet. Nornis keeps those distinct — player-visible truth and GM truth never blur.
    </p>

    <h2>The name</h2>
    <p>
        The Norns of Norse myth tend the roots of the world-tree and weave what has happened into
        what endures. Nornis does the humbler, table-sized version of that job: many branches
        feeding a single trunk — many sources, one enduring epic.
    </p>
</article>
